    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what do u mean by a sneaky little creature lol? anyway i'm mostly worried about the corners. how do i make sure the corners don't crack or look weird once the paint goes on? i want it to look professional.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Haha, the sneaky little creature is just a metaphor for those tiny, annoying imperfections that try to sneak their way into your perfectly smooth wall!\n\nFor the corners, you need to treat them like a tricky little trap that needs a sturdy, well-hidden barrier. When you're dealing with corners, you can't just slap mud on; you need to create a proper \"cove\" or \"chamfer\" where the two surfaces meet.\n\nStart by applying your tape and mud right into the corner, making sure the mud flows smoothly around the intersection. Instead of just pressing the mud in, you want to build up a slight, rounded transition. This rounded edge is what prevents those sharp, ugly lines that look like a poorly executed piece of work.\n\nOnce you've built up the mud in the corner, use a wider taping knife or a flexible tool to gently blend the mud into the adjacent flat surfaces. You are essentially trying to make the corner look like it was *always* part of the wall, not something you just patched on. If you let the mud dry too fast, the corner will look sharp, and that's when the paint will highlight every single flaw.\n\nA little tip from the old days",
      "source": "target",
